==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|pæþ|lang=ang}}, from West {{etyl|gem}} *''paþaz'', an early borrowing from an Iranian language (Avestan ''pɑntɑ'', gen. ''pɑθɑ'' 'way', Old Persian ''pɑthi-''), in which case it would be derived from the same [[Indo-European]] root as English {{term|find}} (namely, {{proto|Indo-European|pent-}}).  Cognate with Dutch {{term|pad|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Pfad|lang=de}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/pæθ/}}
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/pɑːθ/|/pæθ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-path.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɑːθ}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{sense|concrete}}
## a [[trail]] for the use of, or worn by, [[pedestrian]]s.
## a [[course]] taken.
## {{context|paganism}} A [[pagan|Pagan]] tradition, for example [[witchcraft]], [[Wicca]], [[druidism]], [[Heathenry]].
# {{context|abstract}}
## a [[metaphorical]] course.
## a [[method]] or [[direction]] of proceeding.
## a [[sequence]] (in the [[graph theory]]) of [[vertex|vertices]] from one vertex to another using the arcs ([[edge|edges]]). A path does not visit the same vertex more than once (unless it is a ''closed path'', where only the first and the last vertex are the same).

